{{Orphan|date=March 2014}}

 
{{About||the South Dakota politician and federal judge of this name|Joseph H. Bottum}}

'''Joseph Bottum''' (often nicknamed <U+201C>Jody,<U+201D><ref>Richard John Neuhaus, [http://www.leaderu.com/ftissues/ft9502/public.html <U+201C>While We<U+2019>re At It<U+201D>], ''First Things'', February 1995</ref> born 30 April 1959) is an American author, best known for his writings about poetry, American religion, and [[Neoconservatism|neoconservative]] politics. Born in [[Vermillion, South Dakota]], he was brought up in the state capital of [[Pierre, South Dakota|Pierre]] and later [[Salt Lake City]], Utah, where he attended [[Judge Memorial Catholic High School]].<ref>Jill Callison, [http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/argusleader/doc/912139510.html <U+201C>Memoirs of S.D. rearing<U+201D>], Sioux Falls ''Argus Leader'', December 18, 2011</ref> He lives in the [[Black Hills]] of South Dakota, in the town of [[Hot Springs, South Dakota|Hot Springs]].<ref> Mary Garrigan, [http://rapidcityjournal.com/lifestyles/author-joseph-bottum-writes-bestsellers-from-his-home-in-hot/article_0f7abc69-0ff1-590e-8aba-ff2de4cc94e8.html <U+201C>Author Joseph Bottum writes bestsellers from his home in Hot Springs<U+201D>], ''Rapid City Journal'', December 23, 2012</ref>
A graduate of [[Georgetown University]], with a Ph.D. in philosophy from [[Boston College]], Bottum is a Contributing Editor to the [[Weekly Standard]].<ref>[http://www.weeklystandard.com/tws/aboutus/default.asp ''Weekly Standard'' masthead]</ref> His books include the childhood memoir ''The Christmas Plains'', the examination of song lyrics as poetry in ''The Second Spring'', and the sociological study of American religion in ''An Anxious Age: The Post-Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of America''. His work for Amazon<U+2019>s e-book essay series [[Kindle single|Kindle Singles]] includes the #1 Amazon e-book bestseller<ref>[http://www.thinreads.com/content/interview/4/joseph_bottum <U+201C>Meet Joseph Bottum, One of the World's Most Prolific E-Book Single Authors,<U+201D>] ''Thin Reads'' interview, March 2012</ref> ''Dakota Christmas''. Bottum<U+2019>s 2012 ''The Summer of 43'' was chosen by Amazon as one of the <U+201C>10 Best Kindle Singles of the Year.<U+201D><ref>[http://www.amazon.com/b/ref=sr_aj?node=5917168011&ajr=0 Best Books of 2012 <U+203A> Kindle Edition]</ref> Coverage of his work includes profiles in [[South Dakota Magazine]],<ref>Bernie Hunhoff, [http://southdakotamagazine.com/nov-dec-2012 <U+201C>Why the Bottums Belong in South Dakota<U+201D>], ''South Dakota Magazine,'' November/December 2012</ref> the [[Washington Times]],<ref>Patrick Hruby, [http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/dec/13/e-book-re-kindles-writers-career/?page=all <U+201C>Surprise Kindle Single best-seller a <U+2018>Dakota Christmas<U+2019> present for conservative writer<U+201D>], ''Washington Times,'' December 13, 2011</ref> and the [[New York Times]].<ref>Mark Oppenheimer, [http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/24/us/a-conservative-catholic-now-backs-same-sex-marriage.html?_r=0 <U+201C>A Conservative Catholic Now Backs Same-Sex Marriage<U+201D>], ''New York Times,'' August 23, 2013</ref>
== Professional career ==

Bottum was Assistant Professor of Medieval Philosophy at [[Loyola University Maryland]] from 1993 to 1994, before joining the journal [[First Things]] in New York City as Associate Editor from 1995 to 1997.<ref>[http://www.leaderu.com/ftissues/ft9502/public.html <U+201C>While We<U+2019>re At It<U+201D>]</ref> He moved to Washington, D.C., in 1997, hired by [[William Kristol]] to be Literary Editor of the neoconservative political magazine, the [[Weekly Standard]],<ref>[http://www.weeklystandard.com/Content/Protected/Articles/000/000/008/906htlqz.asp <U+201C>We Are Proud to Announce . . .<U+201D>], ''Weekly Standard,'' November 17, 1997</ref> while also serving as Poetry Editor of ''First Things'' from 1998 to 2004.<ref>[http://www.firstthings.com/article/2010/04/rhyme-reason <U+201C>Rhyme & Reason,<U+201D> ''First Things,'' April 2010]</ref> In 2004, the founder of ''First Things'', [[Richard John Neuhaus]], brought him back to New York as the new Editor of ''First Things''.<ref>Neuhaus, [http://www.firstthings.com/article/2009/02/america-as-a-religion <U+201C>While We<U+2019>re At It<U+201D>], ''First Things,'' February 2009.</ref> Forced out in 2010 after controversy about the future and the funding of the magazine<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/dec/13/e-book-re-kindles-writers-career/?page=all ''Washington Times'' profile]</ref> following the death of Neuhaus, Bottum moved to his family<U+2019>s summer house in the Black Hills of South Dakota.<ref>Mary Garrigan, [http://rapidcityjournal.com/lifestyles/southern-hills-solitude-suits-catholic-author/article_ef8d0418-5411-11e1-bd85-0019bb2963f4.html <U+201C>Southern Hills solitude suits Catholic author<U+201D>], ''Rapid City Journal'', February 11, 2012</ref>
After returning to South Dakota, he produced his Kindle Single ''Dakota Christmas'', which reached #1 on the Amazon e-book bestseller list, and he published three print books<U+2014>''The Second Spring'' (2011), ''The Christmas Plains'' (2012), and ''An Anxious Age'' (2014)<U+2014>together with the e-book collection of selected essays, ''Pulp & Prejudice,'' and four additional Kindle Singles for Amazon: sports Singles on [[Tim Tebow]] and [[R.A. Dickey]], and Bottum<U+2019>s annual Christmas fiction ''Wise Guy'' and ''Nativity.''<ref>[http://rapidcityjournal.com/news/local/communities/hot-springs/community/author-releases-christmas-e-story/article_6307d0d0-666c-11e3-81db-001a4bcf887a.html <U+201C>Author releases Christmas e-story<U+201D>], ''Hot Springs Star'', December 16, 2013</ref>
His widely cited essays include <U+201C>The Soundtracking of America<U+201D><ref>Bottum, [http://www.theatlantic.com/past/docs/issues/2000/03/bottum.htm <U+201C>The Soundtracking of America<U+201D>] ''Atlantic, '' March 2000</ref> in [[The Atlantic]], <U+201C>What T.S. Eliot Almost Believed<U+201D><ref>Bottum, [http://www.leaderu.com/ftissues/ft9508/articles/bottum.html <U+201C>What T.S. Eliot Almost Believed<U+201D>] ''First Things'', August/September 1995</ref> and <U+201C>Christians and Postmoderns<U+201D><ref>Bottum, [http://www.firstthings.com/article/2009/03/004-christians-and-postmoderns-27 <U+201C>Christians and Postmoderns<U+201D>], ''First Things'', February 1994</ref> in ''First Things'', and <U+201C>The Myth of the Catholic Voter<U+201D><ref>Bottum, [http://www.weeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/004/818vklel.asp <U+201C>The Myth of the Catholic Voter<U+201D>], ''Weekly Standard'', November 1, 2004 / November 8, 2004</ref> and <U+201C>The Last Public Poet: Re-Reading Robert Lowell<U+201D><ref>Bottum, [http://staging.weeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/002/940kqmzb.asp <U+201C>The Last Public Poet: Re-Reading Robert Lowell<U+201D>], ''Weekly Standard'', August 4 / August 11, 2003</ref> in the ''Weekly Standard''. 

Bottum<U+2019>s essays, poems, and reviews have appeared in the ''Wall Street Journal'', the ''Washington Post'', ''USA Today'', ''The Times'' of London, and other newspapers; ''Forbes'', ''Newsweek'', ''Commentary'', ''Standpoint'', and other magazines; the ''International Philosophical Quarterly'', ''U.S. Catholic Historian'', ''Nineteenth-Century Literature'', and other scholarly journals. His work has been anthologized in ''Best Spiritual Writing 2010'', ''Best Catholic Writing 2007'', ''Best Christian Writing 2004'', ''The Conservative Poets'', ''Why I Turned Right'', etc., and translated and republished in German, Italian, Polish, Portuguese, etc.<ref> [http://www.randomhouse.com/book/16449/an-anxious-age-by-joseph-bottum#abouttheauthor <U+201C>Joseph Bottum<U+201D>], Random House author description</ref>
Bottum<U+2019>s 2013 essay <U+201C>The Things We Share<U+201D><ref>Bottum, [https://www.commonwealmagazine.org/things-we-share <U+201C>The Things We Share<U+201D>], ''Commonweal,'' August 23, 2013</ref> in the Catholic journal [[Commonweal Magazine|Commonweal]], urging acceptance of state-sanctioned same-sex marriage, was covered by a pair of articles in the ''New York Times''<ref>Mark Oppenheimer, [http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/24/us/a-conservative-catholic-now-backs-same-sex-marriage.html?_r=0 <U+201C>A Conservative Catholic Now Backs Same-Sex Marriage<U+201D>], ''New York Times,'' August 23, 2013, and Ross Douthat, [http://douthat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/08/26/what-joseph-bottum-wants/ <U+201C>What Joseph Bottum Wants<U+201D>], August 26, 2013.</ref> and by many other publications. Widely cited and attacked, it led to the ostracizing of Bottum in some conservative and religious circles.<ref>Matthew Boudway, [https://www.commonwealmagazine.org/blog/reply-joseph-bottums-conservative-critics <U+201C>A Reply to Joseph Bottum's Conservative Critics<U+201D>], ''Commonweal'', August 30, 2013</ref> Other controversial positions Bottum has taken include his opposition to the death penalty,<ref>Steve Bainbridge, [http://mirrorofjustice.blogs.com/mirrorofjustice/2005/08/bottum_on_the_d.html <U+201C>Bottum on the Death Penalty<U+201D>], ''Mirror of Justice'', August 5, 2005</ref> his defense of [[Pope Pius XII]],<ref>Vincent A. Lapomarda, S.J., [http://www.newoxfordreview.org/briefly.jsp?did=1105-briefly review of ''The Pius War''], ''New Oxford Review'', November 2005</ref> and his rejection of abortion: <U+201C>the evil of abortion is Bottum<U+2019>s whole conservative philosophy,<U+201D> as one commentator complained in <U+201C>The Fundamental Conflict in Joseph Bottum<U+2019>s Thought.<U+201D><ref>Fr. Edmund Waldstein, [http://sancrucensis.wordpress.com/2013/08/27/the-fundamental-conflict-in-joseph-bottums-thought/ <U+201C>The Fundamental Conflict in Joseph Bottum<U+2019>s Thought<U+201D>], ''Sancrucensis'', August 27, 2013</ref>
Bottum<U+2019>s 2014 book ''An Anxious Age: The Post-Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of America'' argues that members of the nation's elite class are the spiritual heirs of [[Mainline Protestant|Mainline Protestantism]], and that this class has triumphed over Catholics and Evangelicals in the culture wars.<ref>David Goldman, [http://www.the-american-interest.com/articles/2014/03/17/the-rise-of-secular-religion/ review of ''An Anxious Age''], the ''American Interest'', March 17, 2014</ref> In an article attacking him for his stance on same-sex marriage, [[National Review]] nonetheless wrote, <U+201C>Bottum is the poetic voice of modern Catholic intellectual life. His work . . . shaped the minds of a generation.<U+201D><ref>J. D. Flynn, [http://m.nationalreview.com/corner/356886/trampling-fumie-j-d-flynn <U+201C>Trampling the Fumie<U+201D>], ''National Review'', August 27, 2013</ref>
Bottum has read his [[New Formalism|New Formalist]] poetry on [[C-SPAN]],<ref>[http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/184060-1 <U+201C>Poetry Readings for Children<U+201D>]</ref> done commentary for NBC<U+2019>s [[Meet the Press]]<ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/7619740/#.UWb9EIKpabM ''Meet the Press'' <U+201C>Transcript for April 24<U+201D>]</ref> and the [[PBS Newshour]],<ref>[http://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/2009/12/on-thursdays-newshour.html <U+201C>On Thursday's NewsHour<U+201D>]</ref> and appeared on many other television and radio programs. His relatives include great-uncle and namesake [[Joseph H. Bottum]] (the 1960s South Dakota senator), cousin [[Roddy Bottum]] (keyboardist for the rock band Faith No More), and cousin Russell Hittinger<ref>[http://www.utulsa.edu/academics/colleges/Henry-Kendall-College-of-Arts-and-Sciences/Departments-and-Schools/Department-of-Philosophy-and-Religion/Our-Faculty-and-Staff/H/FRussellHittinger.aspx Francis Russell Hittinger]</ref> (the Catholic philosopher).

== Publications ==

*''An Anxious Age: The Post-Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of America'' (Image/Random House, 2014)
*''The Christmas Plains'' (Image/Random House, 2012)
*''The Second Spring: Words Into Music, Music Into Words'' (St. Augustine<U+2019>s Press, 2011) 
*(co-editor) ''The Pius War: Responses to the Critics of Pius XII'' (Lexington Books, 2004)
*''The Fall & Other Poems'' (St. Augustine<U+2019>s Press, 2001) 
*''Nativity: A Christmas Tale'' (Kindle Single e-book, 2013)
*''Wise Guy: A Christmas Tale'' (Kindle Single e-book, 2012)
*''The Summer of 43: R.A. Dickey's Knuckleball and the Redemption of America<U+2019>s Game'' (Kindle Single e-book, 2012) 
*''The Gospel According to Tim'' (Kindle Single e-book, 2012)
*''Pulp & Prejudice: Essays in Search of Books, Culture, and God'' (Amazon e-book, 2011)
*''Dakota Christmas'' (Kindle Single e-book, 2011)

